         <abstract>
            <p>As it is usually defined, risk arbitrage involves purchasing the stock of the target firm in a takeover attempt that has been publicly announced. Once the sole domain of the professional investor, merger and acquisition arbitrage has recently attracted a considerable amount of "outside" capital. A consequence of this increased speculative participation is that the post-announcement stock prices of the merging firms reflect the market's consensus prediction that the venture will ultimately be successful. This paper presents a simple technique based on the mechanics of the risk arbitrage process for estimating the probability of a successful corporate takeover. Empirical evidence is provided to support the conclusion that the market can meaningfully discriminate between those merger proposals that will be completed and those that will eventually fail far in advance of the actual outcome.</p>
         </abstract>
